# Summary of Code of Conduct enforcement decisions
The elected Token House Code of Conduct Council’s decisions are subject to optimistic approval by the Token House. That means the Council’s decisions are assumed to be approved unless 12% of the votable supply in the Token House votes to veto an enforcement action. You should only cast a vote if you want to override the decisions made by the Council. If this proposal is veto-d, the enforcement actions will go to a full Token House vote. 

This proposal is eligible for Voting Cycle #17: 
<https://gov.optimism.io/t/code-of-conduct-council-communication-thread/7453>

# Mission Requests: Intent #1 1.33M OP
In Season 5, the Token House will approval rank Mission Requests that work towards our Collective Intents. Mission Requests outline specific initiatives aimed at achieving one of the Intents. Once approved, teams will apply to fulfill each Request by submitting a Mission Application. Below are the Mission Requests under Intent #1: Progress towards technical decentralization. 

NOTE: YOU WILL NOT BE ABLE TO CHANGE YOUR VOTE ONCE CAST

This vote utilizes approval voting. Mission Requests will be approval ranked based on the number of yes votes. Each Mission Request must receive a minimum number of yes votes, equal to 51% of quorum. Any Mission that does not receive > required number of yes votes will not qualify for a budget allocation. The top ranked Requests, above the minimum number of yes votes, will be accepted until the Intent Budget runs out. If a Mission would push the Intent Budget over the approved amount, it will not be included. Any Intent Budgets left over will be returned to the Governance Fund. For examples, see [How to Vote on Missions Guide](https://gov.optimism.io/t/how-to-vote-on-mission-requests/6203).

As a voter, you should vote yes on all Mission Requests you think should be approved, and you should abstain from voting on Mission Requests you do not think should be approved. You can view some guidelines on factors to consider [here](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-evaluations/7553).

--

# Season 6: Developer Advisory Board Renewal  
The Token House experimented with a Developer Advisory Board in Season 5. It is now time for delegates to assess whether the Board should be renewed. 

Delegates may choose to approve an operating budget for the Developer Advisory Board to continue in Season 6. The operating budget with the highest number of “Yes” votes will be approved, electing the proposal author as Council Lead. If delegates do not believe the Developer Advisory Board should continue, they should not approve any operating budget for a Developer Advisory Board.

This vote utilizes approval voting, allowing delegates to cast votes for multiple options with their full voting power cast for each option chosen. It is recommended that you only cast one vote to approve one operating budget (or don’t cast any votes if you do not wish to renew the Board.) 

The first proposed DAB Operating Budget is by Zach Obront, with a budget of 90k OP: <https://gov.optimism.io/t/zach-obront-developer-advisory-board-operating-budget/8141>

The second proposed DAB Operating Budget is by Ed Mazurek (wildmolasses), with a budget of 122k OP: <https://gov.optimism.io/t/ed-mazurek-developer-advisory-board-operating-budget/8175> 

This proposal is eligible for Special Voting Cycle #23a: <https://gov.optimism.io/t/season-6-developer-advisory-board-renewal/8099>

# Mission Requests: Intent #1, 500k OP

Below are the Mission Requests under Intent #1: Progress Towards Technical Decentralization: Governance. These Mission Requests should work towards the below target metrics: 

**Token House governance:** Increase votable supply by 15% to 100M OP

**Citizens’ House governance:** Increase in the percentage of Citizens that feel confident voting on upgrade vetos (to be measured via the voting UI in each veto proposal)

**Mission Requests are shown in the order suggested by the Collective Feedback Commission.** As a voter, you may vote in order to accept the suggestion of the Collective Feedback Commission or you may vote according to your own preferences. You should vote yes on all Mission Requests you think should be approved, and you should abstain from voting on Mission Requests you do not think should be approved. The top 5 most-voted candidates will be elected to the Season 6 Code of Conduct Council. You can review a video recording of the candidate town hall [here](https://gov.optimism.io/t/code-of-conduct-council-s6-election-town-hall/8627).

This vote will utilize approval voting. Voting is set up such that you can place a vote for any number of nominees. In the case of approval/ranked choice votes, delegates may vote for themselves, so long as they also cast votes for the remaining elected positions.

# Rolling Mission Requests: Voting Cycle 27
Contingent on approval of the Rolling Mission Requests proposal, the Token House will approval rank rolling Mission Requests proposed under Intent 3A: Grow Application Developers on OP Mainnet. These Mission Requests should work towards the below target metric:

Target metric: 9,500 active developers driving usage across the Superchain

As a voter, you should vote yes on all Mission Requests you think should be approved, and you should abstain from voting on Mission Requests you do not think should be approved.

NOTE: YOU WILL NOT BE ABLE TO CHANGE YOUR VOTE ONCE CAST

This vote utilizes approval voting. Mission Requests will be approval ranked based on the number of yes votes. Each Mission Request must receive a minimum number of yes votes, equal to 51% of quorum, and fall within the ranking eligible to receive budget allocation. For more details, please see [How to Vote on Missions Guide](https://gov.optimism.io/t/how-to-vote-on-mission-requests/6203). 

*Intent 3A: Grow Application Developers on OP Mainnet, 6M OP Budgeted*
Mission Requests

Request 1: [Subsidized Audit Grants V2](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-subsidized-audit-grants-v2/8856), 250.000 OP

Request 2: [Experimentation of Infrastructure Subsidies](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-experimentation-of-infrastructure-subsidies/8851) 250.000 OP

Request 3: [Superchain Borrow/Lend Aggregator](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-superchain-borrow-lend-aggregator/8811) 30.000 OP

Request 4: [Crosschain alert monitoring](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-subsidized-audit-grants-v2/8856) 60.000 OP

Request 5: [Optimism Dominance in Yield-Bearing Assets - DEX Liquidity for YBAs](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-optimism-dominance-in-yield-bearing-assets-dex-liquidity-for-ybas/8817) 500.000OP


Request 6: [ Decentralized Solvers and Aggregators on OP Mainnet / Superchain](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-decentralized-solvers-and-aggregators-on-op-mainnet-superchain/8852) 250.000 OP

Request 7: [Targeted extension of Superfest](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-targeted-extension-of-superfest/8854) 350.000 OP

Request 8: [Optimism Full Financial Audit](https://gov.optimism.io/t/mission-request-optimism-full-financial-audit/8826) 20.000 OP

# Security Council Elections Cohort B Members



 ## Description 
Following the guidelines of the [Security Council Charter](https://github.com/ethereum-optimism/OPerating-manual/blob/main/Security%20Council%20Charter%20v0.1.md), the Token House will hold elections for Cohort B of the Optimism Security Council. The top 6 candidates with the highest votes will be elected to Cohort B and serve a 12-month term, subject to Foundation confirmation. If any candidate is not confirmed by the Foundation, the runner up will take their position.


This vote will utilize approval voting, allowing delegates to vote for any number of nominees. In approval or ranked choice votes, delegates may vote for themselves as long as they also cast votes for the remaining elected positions.

# Maintenance Upgrade: L1 Pectra Readiness
Pectra is an [upgrade to the Ethereum protocol](https://docs.optimism.io/notices/pectra-changes) composed of Prague (Execution Layer) and Electra (Consensus Layer) which will activate soon on testnets and mainnet. It contains consensus changes which, by default, would cause all OP Stack chains to halt. In particular:

- a new transaction type (and corresponding receipt type) is introduced by [EIP-7702](https://vote.optimism.io/proposals/create).
- a new field in the block header is introduced by [EIP-7685](https://eips.ethereum.org/EIPS/eip-7685)

Upgrade 12 is a maintenance upgrade which consists of changes to
- Node software
- Optimism protocol specifications and
- L1 Fault Proofs smart contract system(s) to elegantly handle activation of the Pectra hardfork on L1 networks.

The expected outcome is that OP Stack chains continue to operate as before (they do not halt) when Pectra activates on their respective L1 chains. This is a critical piece of maintenance affecting all operators and users of OP Stack chains.

Key Dates
- Activation of Pectra on Holesky: 24th February 2025
- Activation of Pectra on Sepolia: 5th March 2025
- Activation of Pectra on Mainnet: 8th April 2025 (provisional)

Read the Maintenance Upgrade proposal in its entirety [here](https://gov.optimism.io/t/upgrade-proposal-12-l1-pectra-readiness/9706).

This is an optimistic approval. Voters will be asked to vote for, against, or abstain. The proposal will automatically pass unless 12% of votable supply vote against. The proposal will concurrently be in the citizens house during this optimistic approval window. You can read more about this proposal type in our [operating manual](https://github.com/ethereum-optimism/OPerating-manual/blob/main/manual.md).
